article.description: Reggie Miller scored 28 points after serving a suspension and the Pacers got back on track with a 106-88 victory over the road-weary Los Angeles Clippers.
article.headline: Pacers' defense, Miller's 28 points trip Clips
article.linkText: New Bad Boys? Thomas' Pacers ride defense past Clips
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The new Indiana Pacers are beginning to resemble Isiah Thomas' old Detroit Pistons.
Reggie Miller

Reggie Miller scored a season-high 28 points and Jermaine O'Neal added 22 as the Pacers beat the Los Angeles Clippers 106-88 Saturday night. Thomas believed the acquisition of Ron Artest, Ron Mercer, Brad Miller and Kevin Ollie in a trade with Chicago would make the Pacers tougher and improve them defensively. So far, he likes the results. "We can turn into a hellacious defensive unit out there," Indiana's second-year coach said. "Our offense will generate points from the defense. We played in spurts defensively about as good as I've seen any team play since those Pistons teams." The Pacers had a 22-point lead cut to six with 8 minutes left in the game before going on a 14-2 run. O'Neal started the surge with a basket and Jeff Foster ended it with consecutive baskets. Indiana used a 25-6 run in the second to take an early lead. Artest, showing little effects of a sprained left ankle, came off the bench to score 12 points in the quarter. Artest had three steals and several other outstanding plays. After scoring a basket that gave the Pacers a 10-point lead, he knocked the inbounds pass off a Clipper. Miller took advantage of the possession and hit a 3-pointer. Twice in the third quarter, Artest forced jump balls with Elton Brand. Artest came up behind Brand and tried to grab a rebound out of his hands. Three possessions later, they were tied up fighting for a loose ball. "We ran the ball well, played defense, hacked and knocked the ball loose and really made an extreme effort," Artest said. "I know what my job is." The Pacers, outrebounded by 18 boards on Friday, finished with a 50-44 rebounding advantage. Brad Miller scored 14 and Jonathan Bender and Artest each had 13 for the Pacers. Jeff Foster grabbed 14 rebounds. "That type of defensive mindset -- a lot of players don't think that way," Thomas said. "Those are the kind of guys I like. Jeff already had that mindset. Artest brings that mindset. Ollie brings that mindset." Reggie Miller went 8-for-13, while O'Neal bounced back from a poor shooting night Friday to make 10 of 18 shots. Reggie Miller played his first game with his new teammates after serving a one-game suspension on Friday. He said he noticed the difference in Indiana's defensive approach. "We were probably more offensively gifted with Jalen (Rose) and Travis (Best)," he said. "But we've predicated ourselves on defense. Tonight was a good indication of that." Clippers coach Alvin Gentry said the Pacers may be adding new players, but it's Miller who has the most impact. "He changed the outlook," he said. "Look at the team they had last night and the team they put out there tonight. It's entirely different. Reggie Miller is always a threat to score." Brand had 23 points and tied a career high with 21 rebounds and Jeff McInnis scored 23 points for the Clippers. Michael Olowokandi added 15 and Quentin Richardson 12. Indiana led by 15 at the end of the third, but the Clippers opened the fourth with a 15-2 run. Richardson hit a 3 that made it 89-79. Brand scored on a tip-in, and a basket by Richardson made it 89-83, but the Clippers did not score again until late in the game.

Game notes
Darius Miles started in place of Corey Maggette, who was placed on the injured list Friday with a hand injury. ... World Wrestling Federation ring announcer Lilian Garcia sang the national anthem. ...The Pacers play six of their next seven games on the road. ...The Pacers (24.4) and the Clippers (24.8) are the two youngest teams in the NBA. ... Miles and Richardson fouled out. ...The Pacers are 14-1 when they hold the opposition to less than 90 points.
